  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most owner-occupiers who sell a property also need to buy one. The two transactions are financially linked: the equity from the sale typically funds a significant part of the next purchase. The challenge is that property transactions in Queensland do not automatically synchronise. Two separate contracts, two separate sets of parties, two separate banks, and two separate conveyancers need to arrive at settlement at the right time relative to each other. When they do not, the consequences can range from a stressful few days of bridging to a genuinely difficult financial position. Getting this right requires clear planning from the outset.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The core challenge: two timelines that do not automatically align</h2>
      <p>A standard Queensland residential contract allows for a 30 to 60-day settlement period from the date of contract, though this is negotiable. If you sell your current home on a 45-day settlement and buy your next home on a 30-day settlement, you will own both properties simultaneously for a period and need to fund the second purchase before the first one settles. This is manageable for buyers who have significant cash reserves or access to equity outside the sale, but for most owner-occupiers, it means a short-term funding gap that needs to be covered by bridging finance.</p>

      <p>Conversely, if you sell on a 30-day settlement and buy on a 45-day settlement, you will have a period where you have sold your home but not yet settled on your purchase. You will need somewhere to live for that gap and you will need to understand what happens to the proceeds of your sale in the meantime. These misalignments are common and entirely manageable, but they need to be anticipated rather than discovered at the last minute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Making contracts conditional</h2>
      <p>One of the most effective ways to manage the timing risk is to build a condition into one or both contracts. The most common approach is to make your purchase contract conditional on the settlement of your sale. This condition, sometimes called a "subject to sale" clause, means you are not locked into completing the purchase if your existing sale falls through before settlement.</p>

      <p>Subject to sale conditions are common in Queensland but they do reduce your attractiveness as a buyer. Sellers and their agents know that a conditional buyer carries more risk than an unconditional one, and in a competitive market, a subject to sale offer may be passed over in favour of a cleaner offer at a similar price. In Brisbane's inner east, where well-presented properties regularly attract multiple offers, leading with a subject to sale condition can mean missing out on properties that are moving quickly.</p>

      <p>The alternative is to make your offer unconditionally but time the settlement carefully. If you have confidence your current home will sell quickly and your lender can provide bridging finance if needed, an unconditional offer with a settlement date that aligns with your expected sale settlement is often the more competitive approach. The risk is that if your sale takes longer than expected, you need to fund both properties simultaneously until it catches up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bridging finance as a fallback</h2>
      <p>Bridging finance is a short-term loan that covers the gap between your purchase settlement and your sale settlement. If you need to complete your purchase before your sale proceeds are available, your lender advances the purchase funds and then repays that advance from your sale proceeds when they land. The loan sits on interest during the bridging period, which is typically a few weeks to a few months.</p>

      <p>The cost of bridging finance is not trivial, but for short bridging periods of four to eight weeks, it is usually manageable relative to the value of the transactions. The key requirements are that your lender is satisfied you can service the bridging loan while holding both properties, and that the sale of your existing home is contracted and unconditional before the bridging period begins. Most lenders will not provide bridging finance against a sale that is still conditional.</p>

      <p>If you are planning to use bridging finance as your fallback, talk to your lender before you start your search, not after you have found a property. Understanding your bridging capacity in advance means you can move quickly and with confidence when the right property comes along, rather than losing time negotiating with the bank while the seller waits for your finance condition to be satisfied.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How agents help coordinate settlement timing</h2>
      <p>A good selling agent understands that for most of their vendors, the sale does not happen in isolation. If you are buying simultaneously, communicating this clearly to your agent from the start means they can factor your timing needs into how they run the campaign and how they negotiate settlement terms with buyers.</p>

      <p>Settlement date is a negotiating point in every Queensland contract. Most buyers and sellers have some flexibility, and many will agree to a settlement date that suits both parties if asked early and clearly. An agent who knows you need a 45-day settlement rather than 30 days can make that a condition of accepting any offer, rather than agreeing to a buyer's preferred terms and leaving you scrambling to align the two transactions later.</p>

      <p>On the purchase side, your buyer's agent or the listing agent on the property you are purchasing can sometimes assist with aligning settlement dates if you are transparent about your situation. Sellers who have already bought their next property often have strong motivation to synchronise their settlements too, which creates genuine room for coordination.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If one settlement falls through</h2>
      <p>The scenario that concerns most simultaneous movers is what happens if one settlement does not proceed. In Queensland, settlement failure can occur if a buyer's finance falls through at the last moment, if a property condition is not met, or in rare cases if one party simply defaults. The consequences for the other transaction depend on whether you have protected yourself with conditions or bridging finance.</p>

      <p>If your sale falls through after you have gone unconditional on your purchase, you may be in a position where you are obligated to complete a purchase you cannot fund. This is the situation bridging finance is designed to address, but it requires your lender to be prepared in advance. If your purchase falls through after you have settled your sale, you have funds available but no home, which is a much more manageable situation financially even if it is disruptive.</p>

      <p>The practical protection is to avoid going unconditional on your purchase before your sale is unconditional. If you can sequence the conditions so that your sale finance approval and building and pest conditions are met before you waive conditions on your purchase, the risk of simultaneous failure is substantially reduced. Your conveyancer should be monitoring both timelines and alerting you if the sequencing is getting out of sync.</p>

